  "text": "The acks producer configuration value propagates through the Kafka codebase in the following chain:\n\n1. CONFIGURATION DEFINITION (ProducerConfig.java): The ACKS_CONFIG constant is defined with valid values 'all' (or '-1'), '0', and '1', with 'all' as the default. The parseAcks() method (line 639) validates and converts the string value 'all' to '-1'.\n\n2. PRODUCER INITIALIZATION (KafkaProducer.java): During producer initialization, the createSender() method reads the acks value from ProducerConfig.getString(ACKS_CONFIG) at line 526, parses it using Short.parseShort(), and passes the numeric short value to the Sender constructor.\n\n3. CLIENT-SIDE SENDING (Sender.java): The Sender class stores the acks value as a private field (line 99). When sending produce requests, sendProduceRequests() passes the acks value to sendProduceRequest() (line 858). The sendProduceRequest() method encodes this value into ProduceRequestData.setAcks(acks) at line 899, which serializes it into the produce request protocol.\n\n4. REQUEST PROTOCOL ENCODING (ProduceRequest.java and ProduceRequest.json): ProduceRequest.java extracts and stores the acks value from ProduceRequestData (line 104). ProduceRequest.json defines the Acks field as an int16 field (line 55) in the protocol, allowing values 0 (no acks), 1 (leader only), or -1 (all in-sync replicas).\n\n5. BROKER REQUEST HANDLING (KafkaApis.scala): The broker's handleProduce() method extracts acks from the incoming ProduceRequest (line 537: produceRequest.acks) and passes it to ReplicaManager.handleProduceAppend() as the requiredAcks parameter. KafkaApis also determines immediate response behavior: for acks=0 (line 499) and acks=1 (line 518), responses are sent immediately without waiting for replica acknowledgment.\n\n6. BROKER APPEND LOGIC (ReplicaManager.scala): The handleProduceAppend() method receives requiredAcks (line 732) and validates it using isValidRequiredAcks() (line 1364), ensuring it is one of -1, 0, or 1. The appendRecords() method (line 674) calls maybeAddDelayedProduce() (line 704) only when requiredAcks == -1.\n\n7. DELAYED PRODUCE DECISION (ReplicaManager.scala and DelayedProduce.scala): The delayedProduceRequestRequired() method (line 1355) checks if delayedProduceRequestRequired(requiredAcks, ...) returns true. This function returns true only when requiredAcks == -1 (line 1358). When true, maybeAddDelayedProduce() creates a DelayedProduce operation (line 919) with ProduceMetadata containing the requiredAcks value.\n\n8. REPLICA ACKNOWLEDGMENT CHECKING (DelayedProduce.scala and Partition.scala): The DelayedProduce operation's tryComplete() method (line 89) checks if pending acks are satisfied by calling partition.checkEnoughReplicasReachOffset() for each partition (line 101). This method (Partition.scala line 1089) checks if the high watermark >= required offset and validates that the minimum ISR requirement is met (lines 1111-1119). The operation completes when all in-sync replicas have acknowledged the write by reaching the required offset, or times out after the configured timeout period.\n\nIn summary:\n- acks=0: Producer doesn't wait for any acknowledgment; broker sends immediate response\n- acks=1: Producer waits for leader acknowledgment; broker sends response after leader appends records\n- acks=-1 (all): Producer and broker wait for all in-sync replicas to acknowledge via the DelayedProduce mechanism, checking replica log end offsets against the required offset"
}

